rket is a case study with lessons applicable to communities throughout North America. Her examination of Aboriginal labour market participation outlines the deeply damaging, intergenerational effects of colonial policies and describes how a neoliberal political economy serves to further exclude Indigenous North Americans. MacKinnon’s work demonstrates that a fundamental shift in policy is required. Long-term financial support for comprehensive, holistic education and training programs that integrate cultural reclamation and small supportive learning environments is needed if we are to improve social and economic outcomes and support the spiritual and emotional healing that Aboriginal learners tell us is of primary importance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman rightsxMuseumsxPolitical aspects. 0aHuman rightsxMuseumsxSocial aspects. 0aMuseum architecture. 0aMuseum exhibitsxCase studies. 0aMuseum exhibits. 0aMuseum studies. 0aMuseums and Indigenous peopleszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh  aIndigenous.  aJob Market.  aLabour.  aManitoba.  aTraining.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755467440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554674423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554674/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles